        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:36:"Dog walker: worst job interview ever";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:81:"http://www.chicagonow.com/new-abides/2015/10/dog-walker-worst-job-interview-ever/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:90:"http://www.chicagonow.com/new-abides/2015/10/dog-walker-worst-job-interview-ever/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 05 Oct 2015 23:12:18 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:44:"http://www.chicagonow.com/new-abides/?p=4468";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3461:"Back when Lilia was about a year old (before Franky was born) I was thinking about picking up some part time work. I saw something online about dog walking and I thought it would be perfect. I was already zipping around the neighborhood with our dog and a stroller twice a day. How hard could it be?

I submitted my information and was contacted by the two owners of the dog walking business. Let us call them, Matt and Kim.

We met up at a sandwich shop where we chatted for a bit. Matt told me he thought I'd be a great addition to their dog walking team. I would only have to attend two onsite interview/training sessions. No problem, Matt!

Later that week, they set me up to meet with Caitlin, a dog walker who was also a school social worker. Everything went as planned. Went to two houses, walked some dogs, all was right in the dog walking world.

We were saying goodbye when Caitlin gave  me a warning. "Just so you know, Kim can be really tough. Try not to let her scare you away." Foreboding. Almost, Shakespearean.

The next day I met up with Kim at a gigantic house in an affluent suburb. Real artwork, a pool, a tennis court and a Shih Tzu we'll call Buffy Buffington III.

Kim sighed as I "freshened up" Buffy's bowl with (gasp!) tap water. Was I supposed to use Evian? Tell me what the rich people do, Kim!

After a walk outside that involved me rambling on to fill the awkward silence, Kim frowned, watching me intently as I picked up after Buffy Buffington III and tied poop up into a little bag. It was amazing. And by amazing, I mean borderline psychotic.

Next up, another suburb with an even fancier house. I'm not sure how I was even allowed in the neighborhood, but I found myself walking into the huge front doors with my new happy gal pal, Kim.

I first noticed the two dogs were baby gated into a laundry room. Then came the overwhelming smell of dog pee.

Oh, yes. A St. Bernard and a French Bulldog hippity hopping in what I can only assume was 20 gallons of pee. Kim's permanent frown defied gravity, and deepened even more. "Cleaning supplies are over there," she said, pointing to a closet and walking away.

After an hour of dutifully mopping the floor, cleaning up the dogs and doling out doggie medication, it was time for us to make an exit. On the way out to our cars, Kim gave me the lowdown.

"I'm not confident that you're ready to join our team. Maybe you can come back for another session and I'll see how you do then."

I really hoped Kim would give me a second chance.

Ah, who am I kidding. I got into my car, peeled out of the fancy neighborhood (there were cobblestone streets so it was kind of hard) and never looked back.

Can you top that? Let's hear your worst interview story!

