Are all of these beaming pictures of children I see on Facebook real? Do your children do things like, smile when you say, "Smile?"

Last week Franky came bounding off the bus and I asked him how picture day went.

"Oh, I didn't smile! The guy said pretty please a bunch of times. I just went like this." (Makes intensely serious face.)

I had told him the day before that if he didn't smile in his picture, he would have to stay in kindergarten an extra year. He called my bluff.

[caption id="attachment_4447" align="alignleft" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/new-abides/files/2015/09/1-20150928_131303.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-4447 " alt="Evil stunt car drivers don't smile." src="http://www.chicagonow.com/new-abides/files/2015/09/1-20150928_131303-300x168.jpg" width="300" height="168" /></a> Evil genius stunt car drivers don't smile.[/caption]

Franky has decided he doesn't like to smile in pictures. He also says he's going to "destroy the earth" and he tells people he's an evil genius.

He is now attending the same school as Lilia. Their P.E. teacher told her that Franky is great, but she questioned his evil genius claims.

Picking up Franky at summer camp, I was surrounded by camp friends asking me if he really is an evil genius. The other day, he jumped off a huge rock while yelling, "Victory is mine!" before running down the sidewalk laughing maniacally.

Turns out, evil geniuses don't smile in pictures.

[caption id="attachment_4449" align="alignright" width="168"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/new-abides/files/2015/09/3-20150822_171022.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-4449" alt="Let me take a picture of your new haircut. Oh well, okay then. " src="http://www.chicagonow.com/new-abides/files/2015/09/3-20150822_171022-168x300.jpg" width="168" height="300" /></a> Let me take a picture of your new haircut. Oh well, okay then.[/caption]

His sister is no help. In fact, she has timed it so that she'll be smiling perfectly for a picture and as soon as the camera goes off, it's crazy face time.

Because of these antics, I like to give out many helpful suggestions while I take their pictures.

"Make a serious face. I mean, a smiling, but serious face. You, over there, stand still for ONE second. I'm not kidding. Can you at least pretend to be happy? Do you ever want to be able to play a video game again in your life? We should probably take a good picture now because we're NEVER COMING BACK!"

Maybe they realize we're not sitting for 19th century portraits and that I can take a million digital photos. Maybe they're just letting their quirky personalities show through.

Or, maybe Franky really is an evil genius that is out to destroy family photography. Only time will tell.

